-- PRESS DIGEST - Hong Kong - Jan 28
-- By Alice Woodhouse
-- Mon Jan 27, 2014 08:56PM EST
-- None



HONG KONG, Jan 28 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Tuesday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST -- Hong Kong's government has banned the sale of live chickens in the territory for three weeks and ordered a cull of 20,000 birds at a wholesale market after a sample from a Guangdong supplier tested positive for H7N9 bird flu. (http://link.reuters.com/tah46v) -- Spending on adertising in Hong Kong reached a record HK$43.1 billion ($5.55 billion)last year with banking and investment industry leading in expenditure in 2013. (http://link.reuters.com/deh46v) -- An injured Indonesian maid has asked a Hong Kong-based domestic helpers' rights group to lodge a compensation claim against her former employer in the city who she alleges beat her. (http://link.reuters.com/beh46v)  THE STANDARD -- Hong Kong's Securities and Futures Commission has begun a consultation on proposals to allow real estate investment trusts to invest in projects or engage in property development and invest in financial instruments. (http://link.reuters.com/geh46v) -- Chow Tai Fook Enterprises unit Chow Tai Fook Nominee will become the second largest shareholder of Bright Smart Securities <1428.HK> as it is set to buy 100 million shares placed by the brokerage at HK$1.30 ($0.17)per share. (http://link.reuters.com/veh46v)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC JOURNAL  -- Total visitor arrivals to Hong Kong in 2013 reached 54.3 million, up 11.7 percent from 2012. Mainland Chinese visiting the city rose 16.8 percent to 40.5 million from a year earlier.